865. Brix appropriately oom- pares Mero. v 2, 90 iam in cur- rum ascendi, iam lora in manus cepi meas. The phrase in ‘manu tenere occurs also Trin. 914. See the crit. note.

866. This and the following line are evidently imitations of some tragic scene or rather re- productione of tragie phraseo- logy. In the present line, the expression sonitus unyularum

apparet is certainly unusual instead of exauditur. In v. 867 we may notice the twofold al- literation in Cursu Celeri, and in Pedum Pernicitas. It is, moreover, foreign to the easy and plain style of comedy to say pedum pernicitas inflexa est instead of pedes pernices in-

flexi sunt.
